Review: one-way ANOVA

Completely randomized design

  • treatments are assigned completely at random to experimental units
  • simplest type of design

\[ \begin{aligned} y_{ij} = \mu + A_i + \epsilon_{ij} \\ \epsilon_{ij} \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \end{aligned} \]

  • \(\mu\) = population mean across treatments
  • \(A\) = treatment A, with levels \(i\) (fixed effects)

Randomized complete blocks (RCB)

Historical roots of RCB: agricultural experiments

Field plots differ in lots of ways: how to minimize the effects of ‘nuisance’ variables?

Use a blocked design! RCB is the simplest kind of blocked design.

RCB ANOVA: example

How does fish abundance affect the abundance and diversity of zooplankton prey?

Treatment: fish abundance

  • control (no cage)
  • low (30 small fish in 3x3m cage)
  • high (90 small fish in 3x3m cage)

Block: location in lake (n = 5)

  • one replicate of each treatment was set up in each location

Response: Levins’ \(D\) (index of richness and abundance)

RCB model

response ~ treatment + block + error

\[ \begin{aligned} y_{ij} = \mu + A_i + B_j + [AB_{ij}] + \epsilon_{ij} \\ \end{aligned} \]

  • \(\mu\) = population mean across treatments
  • \(A\) = treatment A, with levels \(i\)
  • \(B\) = block B, with levels \(j\)
  • \([AB_{ij}]\) = treatment:block interaction, assumed to be 0

In RCB design, each treatment level is represented in each block once.

Hence, this design is considered a two-way ANOVA without replication

Assumptions of RCB model

  • Errors \(\epsilon_{ij}\) are independent, have equal variance, and a normal distribution

  • Additivity: treatment differences are the same for every block and the block differences are the same for every treatment. No interactions.

  • ANOVA and F-test assume balanced data

Visualize data to check for additivity

dat %>% 
  ggplot(aes(treatment, diversity, color = block, group = block)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_path()

Additivity should show up as parallel block trends between treatments.

Linear model with blocking term

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{diversity} = \mu + \text{block} + \text{treatment} + \epsilon \\ \end{aligned} \]

m0 <- lm(diversity ~ 1, data = dat)
m1 <- lm(diversity ~ block, data = dat)
m2 <- lm(diversity ~ block + treatment, data = dat)
anova(m0)
anova(m1)
anova(m2)

Write out, in words, the numerator and denominator for each F-value for m1 and m2.

What does the rule for calculating the F-value using anova appear to be?

Visualizing null vs ANOVA model

Model diagnostics

Check that residuals

  • have a nearly normal distribution
  • no pattern (trend, unequal variance) across blocks
  • no pattern (trend, unequal variance) across treatments
par(mfrow = c(2,2)); plot(m2)

If you need unplanned comparisons, use aov

aov1 <- aov(diversity ~ block + treatment, data = dat)
summary(aov1)
TukeyHSD(aov1)

What do the unplanned comparisons tell you?

What if we remove (inappropriately) the block effect?

m3 <- lm(diversity ~ treatment, data = dat)
anova(m2)
anova(m3)

Inspect the sums of squares for treatment and residuals in both models; do the same for the treatment f-value.

What does this tell you about the block term in the model?
